column10:
The story of the Good Samaritan is a well known story from the Gospel of Luke, but most people don't fully understand it. Most people believe that the story is about hypocrisy. The priest and the Levite are people who should have helped the injured man lying on the side of the road, but they didn't. While it is true that they should have stopped and helped, this is not how the original hearers of the parable would have understood it. 

The priest and the Levite represent groups of people well know by Jesus' first century audience, and they would not have been at all surprised by the priest and Levite's failure to intervene. On this show we will put the story of the Good Samaritan in it's context and apply it to our modern world so that we can better understand the meaning of the text and how Jews in the first century would have seen it. 

Please feel free to attend and be on the show. If you can't make it, be sure to listen to our show. You will be able to find it at www.modernlectionaries.blogspot.com You can also find a sample of what show will be about in my recent May Day speech, also found on my blog. I look forward to hearing from and to seeing some of you there.
column12: The Politician, Rich Man, and Refugee:The Good Samaritan in Contemporary Context

column10:
Using a reading from the apocryphal book of Sirach, otherwise know as Eccelesiasticus, a book popular among first century Christians and still used in the Catholic church, to get a fuller understand how early Christians would have understood the words pride and arrogance when used in the Bible. Too often modern readers understand pride and arrogance as being haughty or full of one's self. When we call someone prideful or arrogant, we think of personal characteristics of individuals who brag or think they are better than us. This is not all of what first century Jews and Christians would have thought.
Instead, early Christians would have thought of the rich and the powerful. They would of thought of bringing the arrogant down from their thrones and "sending the rich away empty" (Luke 1:52-53). They would have thought "impunity."
Join us and be on the show or just listen in. If you can't make it, make sure to listen to the show. You will be able to find it at www.modernlectionaries.blogspot.com. You can also find the reading there for this show. I look forward to hearing from all of you and seeing some of you at the show.
column12: Think Impunity: Understanding Arrogance and Pride in the Bible

There are three Farmers Markets in Braddock District. They all open the week of May 1, 2016; two close the week of October 23; and one stays open until December 17 (but we will not staff there after Election Day).

We are looking for volunteers at each location to staff a table with voter registration forms, campaign literature (including yard signs later in the year), and volunteer sign up forms. All materials will be supplied to you. It is important that completed voter registration forms and volunteer sign ups be returned in a timely manner.

Wakefield Park/ Audrey Moore RECenter (8100 Braddock Rd, Annandale)
Wednesdays, 2:00 - 6:00 pm | May 4 - October 26, 2016

Fairfax County Government Center (12000 Government Center Pkwy, Fairfax)
Thursdays, 3:00 - 7:00 pm | May 5 - October 27, 2016 (except June 9)

Burke VRE (5671 Roberts Pkwy, Burke)
Saturdays, 8:00 am - noon | May 7 - November 5, 2016

Contact <a>[masked]</a> for more information.

Is DL Little Rock for you:
Are you a progressive activist, a progressive layperson, a non-progressive, or a non-drinker in the Central Arkansas area? Then DLLR is for you.

Progressive activists: Are you looking for a low-stress, chilled, and relaxed place to hang out and meet other progressive activists? DLLR is for you.

Progressive layperson: Are you new to Central Arkansas and looking for progressive people and efforts to connect with? Or are you a longtime Arkansan looking for a place to hang out with other progressives. DLLR is for you.

Non-progressives: There are many good, and wonderful, and beautiful persons in Central Arkansas who do not consider themselves progressives, and that's okay. Your presence can prevent groupthink and keep progressives sharp in their reasoning and their love for others. You are welcome to join us. DLLR is for you.

Non-drinker: You may think to yourself, "I don't drink. Am I going to fit in?" Not a problem. "Drinking Liberally" does not mean drink till you get hammered. (In fact, we encourage people to drink responsibly.) It's drink if you want, but you don't have to. Many of us don't, and many of us do. DLLR is for you.

Your presence can prevent groupthink and keep progressives sharp in their reasoning and their love for others. You are welcome to join us. DLLR is for you.

Non-drinker: You may think to yourself, "I don't drink. Am I going to fit in?" Not a problem. "Drinking Liberally" does not mean drink till you get hammered. (In fact, we encourage people to drink responsibly.) It's drink if you want, but you don't have to. Many of us don't, and many of us do. DLLR is for you.

Progressive activists: Are you looking for a low-stress, chilled, and relaxed place to hang out and meet other progressive activists? DLLR is for you.

Progressive layperson: Are you new to Central Arkansas and looking for progressive people and efforts to connect with? Or are you a longtime Arkansan looking for a place to hang out with other progressives. DLLR is for you.

Non-progressives: There are many good, and wonderful, and beautiful persons in Central Arkansas who do not consider themselves progressives, and that's okay. Your presence can prevent groupthink and keep progressives sharp in their reasoning and their love for others. You are welcome to join us. DLLR is for you.

Non-drinker: You may think to yourself, "I don't drink. Am I going to fit in?" Not a problem. "Drinking Liberally" does not mean drink till you get hammered. (In fact, we encourage people to drink responsibly.) It's drink if you want, but you don't have to. Many of us don't, and many of us do. DLLR is for you.

Progressive Coalition Meeting MeetUp for MoveOn, MCPA, DFMC, PDA, and more. We're meeting FOURTH THURSDAYS.

Join us for an important planning and action meeting. We will discuss ways to influence the Congress to support jobs bills , stop global warming, extend healthcare, end wars, and more. We will also discuss state and local politics.

If you haven't already: Please contribute $15 to keep this meetup going. Pay online: http://www.meetup.com... or bring to a meeting.

Saigonese Restaurant,
11232 Grandview Ave Silver Spring (Wheaton), MD 20902
Public Transportation: Short walk from Wheaton Metro (red line)
Google Map: http://maps.google.co...

Ample parking on the street and in a large lot across the street
